{{Infobox World's Fair | box_width = | class = Universal | category = 0 | image = Expo-Milano-1906-Poster.jpg | image_width = | caption = Expo's poster with railwaymen watching Milan from the Simplon Tunnel's portal | year = 1906 | name = Esposizione Internazionale del Sempione | motto = | building = [[Simplon Tunnel]] | area = 100 Ha | invent = | visitors = 7,500,000-10,000,000 | organized = | cnt = 31 | org = | biz = | country = Italy | city = [[Milan]] | venue = Parco Sempione | coord = {{coord|45|28|22.4|N|9|10|28|E|format=dms|type:landmark_region:IT}} | cand = | award = | open = {{start date|df=y|1906|4|28}} | close = {{start date|df=y|1906|11|11}} | prevexpo = [[Liège International (1905)]] | prevcity = [[Liège]] | nextexpo = [[Brussels International 1910]] | nextcity = [[Brussels]] | suppl = | prevsuppl = | prevsupcity = | nextsuppl = | nextsupcity = | simuni = | simspe = | simhor = | simoth = [[International Exhibition (1906)]] | website = }}The '''Milan International''' was a [[world's fair]] held in [[Milan]] in 1906<ref name="FindPell185">{{cite book|first=Findling|last=Pelle|title=Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions|isbn= 978-0-7864-3416-9|chapter=Milan 1906|page=185}}</ref> titled ''L'Esposizione Internazionale del Sempione'', or sometimes ''The Great Expo of Work''.<ref name="milan1906">{{cite web|url=http://www.aboutmilan.com/expo-2015/milan-1906.html|title=World Expo 1906 Milan|accessdate=30 October 2011}}</ref> It received 4,012,776 visits and covered 250 acres.<ref name="FindPell415">{{cite book|first=Findling|last=Pelle|title=Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions|isbn= 978-0-7864-3416-9|chapter=Appendix B:Fair Statistics|page=415}}</ref>
==Summary== [[File:1906 Silver Medal Milan International Exhibition.jpg|thumb|left|[[Art Nouveau]] Silver Medallion by [[Giannino Castiglioni]] to the [[Milan]] International (1906). The South Portal of the [[Simplon Tunnel]] is on the obverse.]] The fair opened on 28 April 1906, ran until 31 October<ref name="FindPell415" /> and marked the opening of the [[Simplon Tunnel]]. The fair was held in [[Parco Sempione|Sempione Park]] and Piazza d'Armi',<ref name="milan1906" /> with the first location hosting fine arts displays and the latter industrial and engineering exhibits, along with the foreign pavilions.<ref name="FindPell185"/> Countries contributing included many from Western Europe,<ref name="FindPell186">{{cite book|first=Findling|last=Pelle|title=Encyclopedia of World's Fairs and Expositions|isbn= 978-0-7864-3416-9|chapter=Milan 1906|page=186}}</ref> [[China]], [[Japan]], [[Turkey]], [[United States]], [[Canada]] and several South American countries shared a pavilion.<ref name="FindPell186" />
==Legacy== The [[International Commission on Occupational Health]] was founded at the Milan International and is still active; and the [[Civic Aquarium of Milan|Milan aquarium]] was built, and is still standing.
[[File:0116 Acq Brunetti.jpg|thumb|[[Civic Aquarium of Milan|Aquarium]] Brunetti built for the Milan International and designed by Sebastiano Giuseppe Locati]]
