In [[architecture]], a '''slipcover''' is a modification of an older [[Facade|building facing]] by adding a new ornamental layer.

The slipcover was a popular treatment in the United States after World War II as early twentieth-century building styles had fallen out of fashion. Constructing a slipcover with a contemporary design over an existing building was a less expensive alternative to tearing down and building anew.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://offcite.org/wp-content/uploads/sites/3/2010/03/EndangeredCity_Homeyer_Cite63.pdf|title=What Lies Beneath|last=Homeyer|first=Paul|publisher=Rice Design Alliance|date=Spring 2005|issue=63|journal=Cite|accessdate=December 2, 2014}}</ref> Sometimes attachments of the slipcover caused damage to the original facings.  At other times, slipcovers have protected the original facings from deterioration.<ref name=wisc>{{cite web|url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/Content.aspx?dsNav=N:4294963828-4294963805&dsRecordDetailS=R:CS4149|title=Removing Metal Panels That Cover Your Historic Commercial Building|publisher=Wisconsin Historical Society|accessdate=December 2, 2014}}</ref>   

