{{Italic title}}
[[File:Bay Bridge reflections at night.gif|thumb|right|300px|A test of The Bay Lights on January 24, 2013]]
[[File:The opening of the Bay Lights.webm|thumb|300px|The opening of the Bay Lights on March 6, 2013]]
[[File:Market Street and the Bay Lights.webm|thumb|right|300px|A time lapse of Market Street, with the Bay Lights in the background]]

'''''The Bay Lights''''' is a [[Site-specific art|site-specific]] monumental light sculpture and [[generative art]] installation on the western span of the [[San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge]], designed to commemorate the 75th&nbsp;anniversary of its opening. The installation by light artist [[Leo Villareal]] includes 25,000 individual white [[Led|LEDs]] along {{convert|1.8|mi}} of the cables on the north side of the suspension span of the bridge between [[Yerba Buena Island]] and [[San Francisco]]. The installation is controlled via a computer and displays changing patterns that are not meant to repeat. The opening ceremony was held on March&nbsp;5, 2013.

Initially intended as a temporary installation, which ended on March&nbsp;5, 2015, the project was re-installed as a longstanding feature of the Bay Bridge with permanent fixtures that were re-lit on January&nbsp;30, 2016.

==Origin==
''The Bay Lights'' was conceived in September 2010 by Ben Davis of Words Pictures Ideas, a public relations company that has a contract with the [[Caltrans|California Department of Transportation]] (Caltrans) for publicizing the construction of the [[Eastern span replacement of the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge|new eastern span replacement]] of the [[San Francisco Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge]] between Yerba Buena Island and Oakland.<ref name="whiting">{{cite news |last=Whiting|first=Sam |title=Bay Bridge to beam vivid light sculpture |url= http://www.sfgate.com/default/article/Bay-Bridge-to-beam-vivid-light-sculpture-3872898.php |accessdate=18 January 2013 |newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=2012-09-18}}</ref> Davis characterized the Bay Bridge as being overshadowed by the [[Golden Gate Bridge]], which is a popular tourist destination for visitors to San Francisco, and he hoped this art project would give the Bay Bridge more recognition.<ref>{{cite news |last=McMenamin|first=Dan |title=Art project to illuminate Bay Bridge |url= http://www.sfexaminer.com/local/2012/09/art-project-illuminate-bay-bridge |accessdate=19 January 2013 |newspaper=Bay City News via [[San Francisco Examiner]] |date=2012-09-18}}</ref>  Davis contacted light artist Leo Villareal, who had an exhibition on display at the [[San Jose Museum of Art]] in late 2010.<ref name="whiting"/>  Davis later founded [[Illuminate the Arts]], a non-profit organization, to organize the sculpture's design, engineering, and fundraising.

Both Davis and Villareal suggest ''The Bay Lights'' was influenced by their experiences at the annual [[Burning Man]] art and music festival in northwestern [[Nevada]].  Villareal first attended Burning Man in 1994 and eventually joined the board of directors of the Burning Man organization. His prototype light sculpture was 16 blinking lights in a grid that was meant to be a beacon when returning to his camp at night.<ref name="fischer"/>  From there, Villareal has programmed more complex light matrices and exhibitions, including his largest, "Multiverse," a 41,000 LED installation on permanent display at the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, DC]].<ref name="whiting"/>

==Operations==

The sculpture is visible mostly from the north side of the bridge and is most easily seen from the San Francisco waterfront. The lights are positioned to be invisible to bridge motorists, to prevent driver distractions.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cuff|first=Dennis |title=25,000 lights to turn Bay Bridge span into giant night sculpture |url= http://www.contracostatimes.com/breaking-news/ci_22269815/25-000-lights-turn-bay-bridge-span-into? |accessdate=18 January 2013 |newspaper=[[Contra Costa Times]] |date=2012-12-27}}</ref>  The installation operates from dusk until dawn daily.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2013/10/16/the-bay-lights-led-sculpture-to-extend-hours-in-november/ |title=The Bay Lights LED Sculpture To Extend Hours In November |date=October 16, 2013 |work=Bay City News Service |publisher=KPIX-TV}}</ref>

===Construction===
The 25,000 white [[LED]]s were attached by construction workers along the vertical steel support cables that connect the deck of the bridge to the suspension cables at the top. Caltrans workers intermittently closed a lane of traffic on the bridge late at night so electricians could install the individual LEDs to the cables.<ref name="fischer">{{cite news |last=Fischer|first=Adam |title=Bright Idea |url= http://tmagazine.blogs.nytimes.com/2012/11/29/bright-idea/ |accessdate=18 January 2013 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=2012-11-29}}</ref><ref name="musiker">{{cite news |last=Musiker|first=Cy |title=Bay Bridge Lightshow on Schedule For March Debut |url= http://www.kqed.org/news/story/2012/12/07/112375/bay_bridge_lighting_project_on_schedule_for_march?category=bay+area |accessdate=19 January 2013 |publisher=[[KQED]] |date=2012-07-12}}</ref> The lights are programmed to create a series of abstract patterns that ascend and descend the cables and appear to cross the bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kuang|first=Cliff |title=Big-Time Techies Want To Turn SF’s Bay Bridge Into A Glittering Light Show |url= http://www.fastcodesign.com/1670002/big-time-techies-want-to-turn-sfs-bay-bridge-into-a-glittering-light-show |accessdate=18 January 2013 |newspaper=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |date=2011-06-11}}</ref> Villareal said the patterns will be inspired by weather patterns, tides, and the volume of traffic on the bridge at any given time.<ref name="sharpe">{{cite news |last=Sharpe|first=Katherine |title=Everything Will Be Illuminated: Artist to Cover Bay Bridge in Programmable LEDs |url= https://www.wired.com/design/2012/05/bay-lights/ |accessdate=18 January 2013 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date=2012-05-29}}</ref> 

The lights need {{convert|100000|ft}} of special cabling to power the installation, as well as for networking and communications with the control computer. The lights are spaced every {{convert|12|in|cm}} and are attached to the bridge with 60,000 zip ties.<ref name="fischer"/>  Each LED bulb can be adjusted for 255 different levels of brightness and the entire installation is controlled remotely by a computer program operated by Villareal.<ref name="whiting"/> The LED lights complement the permanent string of lights that has been attached to the suspension cables since the 50th&nbsp;anniversary of the bridge in 1986.<ref name="whiting"/>

The original, temporary installation, which formally opened on March&nbsp;5, 2013,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2013/03/06/the-bay-lights-officially-unveiled-on-bay-bridge/ |title= ‘The Bay Lights’ Officially Unveiled On Bay Bridge |date= March 6, 2013 |work= |publisher= [[KPIX-TV]] |accessdate= March 6, 2013 }}</ref> was taken down in March 2015 when its permits expired so that Caltrans could repaint and perform maintenance on the cables.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Bay-Lights-Project-Removed-for-Caltrans-Maintenance-on-Bay-Bridge-295077881.html |title=Bay Lights Go Dark for Caltrans Maintenance on Bay Bridge |first=Joe |last=Rosato Jr. |date=4 March 2015 |work=NBC Bay Area |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>  Installation of more robust, permanent lights began in October 2015, and a re-lighting ceremony was held on January 30, 2016,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Bay-Bridge-Lights-Set-to-Shine-Once-Again-6559014.php |title=Bay Lights set to shine once again |first=Douglas |last=Zimmerman |date=9 October 2015 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref><ref name="egelko">{{cite web|last1=Egelko|first1=Bob|title=Bay Bridge light show will go on|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Bay-Bridge-light-show-will-go-on-5964267.php|publisher=SF Gate|accessdate=6 February 2015|date=17 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="cuff">{{cite news |url=http://www.contracostatimes.com/breaking-news/ci_29446187/bay-bridge-light-sculpture-turns-back-saturday-night |title=Bay Bridge light sculpture turns back on Saturday night |first=Denis |last=Cuff |date=28 January 2016 |work=Bay Area News Group |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>  after which the lights were gifted to the state of California.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/morning_call/2016/01/bay-lights-art-installation-bridge-tourism.html |title=Bay Lights art installation to shine again for Super Bowl 50 festivities |first=Todd |last=Johnson |date=29 January 2016 |work=San Francisco Business Times |accessdate=1 February 2016}}</ref>  The new lights are brighter and better able to weather the elements and angled such that they are visible from south of the bridge as well.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ww2.kqed.org/arts/2016/01/29/the-bay-bridge-lights-return-for-an-unlimited-engagement/ |title=The Bay Bridge Lights Return for an Unlimited Engagement |first=Cy |last=Musiker |date=29 January 2016 |work=KQED |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>

===Cost===
The initial project cost $8&nbsp;million, which was raised through private donations and contributions.<ref name="fischer"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Fixes-funding-brighten-Bay-Lights-day-4602033.php |title=Fixes, funding brighten 'Bay Lights' day |first=Michael |last=Cabanatuan |date=June 14, 2013}}</ref>  50&nbsp;million people were estimated to see ''The Bay Lights'' by 2015,<ref name="fischer"/> and the project was estimated to bring up to $100&nbsp;million in tourism revenue to the Bay Area.<ref name="sharpe"/> [[ZERO1 (nonprofit)|ZERO1]], a non-profit dedicated to bringing art and technology together, signed on as the official fiscal sponsor of the project.<ref name="factsheet">{{cite web |url=http://dev.thebaylights.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/The_Bay_Lights_Press_Facts.pdf |title=The Bay Lights Press Facts Sheet |accessdate=June 8, 2013}}</ref>

''The Bay Lights'' is estimated to use approximately $30 per day in electricity,<ref>{{cite news |last=Hoge|first=Patrick |title=Huge Bay Bridge light project going ahead |url= http://www.bizjournals.com/sanfrancisco/blog/2012/09/bay-bridge-light-project-going-ahead.html |accessdate=18 January 2013 |newspaper=[[San Francisco Business Times]] |date=2012-09-18}}</ref> or about $11,000 annually. During the temporary installation period, these costs were covered by a private solar investment company in the form of solar credits.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tarantola|first=Andrew |title=Art Backers Want to Light Up The Bay Bridge |url= https://gizmodo.com/5867523/art-backers-want-to-light-up-the-bay-bridge |publisher=[[Gizmodo]] |accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref>

In July 2014, Illuminate the Arts announced it was partnering with [[Tilt.com]] to sponsor a $1.2 million crowdfunding campaign to keep ''The Bay Lights'' lit until 2026.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kung|first1=Michelle|title=Let There Be Light: 40 Days to Save the Bay Lights|url=http://blog.tilt.com/let-light-40-days-save-bay-lights/|website=Tilt Blog|accessdate=22 August 2014}}</ref>  When the crowdfunding campaign raised less than expected, organizers focused on larger donors and ultimately raised the $4 million necessary to install long-term fixtures.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/4-million-needed-to-save-Bay-Lights-on-Bay-5841174.php |title=$4 million needed to save 'Bay Lights’ on Bay Bridge |first=John |last=King |date=23 October 2014 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>  The [[Bay Area Toll Authority]], which oversees the bridge, agreed to allocate up to $250,000 per year from toll revenues for maintenance and electricity.<ref name="egelko"/>

==Critical reception==
Since its inauguration, ''The Bay Lights'' has received widespread public support and positive reaction, as well as political support from state and local politicians, including [[Jerry Brown|Governor Jerry Brown]], [[Gavin Newsom|Lieutenant Governor Gavin Newsom]], [[Ed Lee (politician)|San Francisco Mayor Ed Lee]], the [[San Francisco Board of Supervisors]] and former [[Willie Brown (politician)|San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown]].<ref name="fischer"/><ref name="sharpe"/>

''[[Hemispheres (magazine)|Hemispheres]]'' named ''The Bay Lights'' the top attraction in its 2013 "Out with the Old, In with the New" Top-25 feature.<ref>{{cite news |title=Out With the Old |url= http://www.hemispheresmagazine.com/2013/01/01/out-with-the-old/ |accessdate=19 January 2013 |publisher=[[United Airlines]] |work=[[Hemispheres (magazine)|Hemispheres]] |date=2013-01-01}}</ref>

On March&nbsp;8, 2014, the documentary ''Impossible Light'' world premiered at the [[SXSW|SXSW Film Festival]]. The film follows the people who wished to produce ''The Bay Lights'' as they search for funding and obtain permits. The ''[[Austin Chronicle]]'' felt that the documentary was a nearly seamless extraction of the evolutionary relationship between art and benefaction.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/daily/screens/2014-03-12/sxsw-film-review-impossible-light/ |title=SXSW Film Review: 'Impossible Light' – |last=Winkler |first=Jeff |date=March 12, 2014 |work=Austin Chronicle}}</ref> The film also screened as part of the 57th [[San Francisco International Film Festival]] and the [[Newport Beach Film Festival]] in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sffs.org/festival-home/attend/film-guide/impossible-light#.UzyRfq1dWjQ|title=Looking Ahead to SFIFF59|work=San Francisco Film Society}}</ref><ref>http://newportbeach2014.festivalgenius.com/2014/films/impossiblelight_jeremyambers_newportbeach2014</ref>

